From: intel-nix
Subject: [PATCH] clang/Driver: check CUDA_PATH env var on Linux too

Clang already checks CUDA_PATH on Windows (where the CUDA installer sets
it).  Package managers on Linux (e.g. NixOS) set CUDA_PATH as well, but
the check is guarded by isOSWindows() so clang never sees it there.

Add the same check into the !cuda_path_ignore_env block that is reached
on non-Windows hosts, tried before the ptxas-in-PATH and /usr/local/cuda
heuristics.

---
 clang/lib/Driver/ToolChains/Cuda.cpp | 6 ++++++
 1 file changed, 6 insertions(+)

diff --git a/clang/lib/Driver/ToolChains/Cuda.cpp b/clang/lib/Driver/ToolChains/Cuda.cpp
--- a/clang/lib/Driver/ToolChains/Cuda.cpp
+++ b/clang/lib/Driver/ToolChains/Cuda.cpp
@@ -169,6 +169,12 @@ CudaInstallationDetector::CudaInstallationDetector(
   } else {
     if (!Args.hasArg(clang::driver::options::OPT_cuda_path_ignore_env)) {
+      // CUDA_PATH may be set by package managers (e.g. NixOS) or the user on
+      // non-Windows systems too.  Check it before the ptxas-in-PATH heuristic
+      // so an explicit env override takes precedence.
+      if (const char *CudaPathEnvVar = ::getenv("CUDA_PATH"))
+        Candidates.emplace_back(CudaPathEnvVar);
+
       // Try to find ptxas binary. If the executable is located in a directory
       // called 'bin/', its parent directory might be a good guess for a valid
       // CUDA installation.
